########## RULES

Use Javascript not typescript

### FOLDERS
This is the folder structure of the React App

src/
    components/          Common, generic reusable components used across multiple pages
    constants/           Files containing constant values and enums
    services/            Service files that make calls to REST APIs
    utils/               Utils files containing reusable util functions, e.g. dateUtils.js
    fetch.service.jsx    Special file with reusable HTTP helpers (get, post, put, delete, etc.)
    pages/               Contains subfolders for each feature/page and their supporting components
        if there are any module specific components they should go in pages/{module}/components
    styles/              Global SCSS (tokens, layout, base styles)

### COMPONENTS

- `src/components/` is for **generic, reusable components** (e.g. Button, Card, Modal, Layout wrappers).
- Feature-specific components that only belong to one page/module should live under that page’s folder, e.g.:
  - `src/pages/users/components/UserTable.jsx`  


### STYLES

- Global SCSS lives under `src/styles/`:
  - `src/styles/_variables.scss` for shared tokens (colors, spacing, typography, radii, etc.)
  - `src/styles/_mixins.scss` for shared mixins (breakpoints, flex helpers, etc.)
  - `src/styles/_layout.scss` for shared layout utilities (page padding, toolbar, sidebar, etc.)
  - `src/styles/main.scss` imports the partials and sets base styles; this is imported once in the app entry point.
- Each React component should have its **own SCSS module file** next to it:
  - `Button.jsx` → `Button.module.scss`
  - `UserPage.jsx` → `UserPage.module.scss`


###MODULES

When creating a new module (e.g. user module), follow this structure:
Service
Create a service file in src/services/:
user.service.jsx
All HTTP calls must use the reusable functions from fetch.service.jsx (no raw fetch or axios in components):

// user.service.jsx
import { get, post, put, del } from './fetch.service';

export function fetchUsers(params) {
  return get('/api/users', { params });
}

export function createUser(payload) {
  return post('/api/users', payload);
}


Pages

Create a folder in src/pages/, e.g. src/pages/users/.
Inside that folder create the main page file, e.g. UserPage.jsx.
Page file should:
Use PageLayout for consistent layout.
Delegate complex UI to smaller components under src/pages/users/components/ if needed.



### DOMAIN and MODELS
To simply code and maintain seperation of concerns
Any business logic should be in a domain object
UserDomain.js
And where apropriate if the data is not simple their should be a model object, e.g. UserModel
UserModel may combine data from multiple APIs
Using the model in combination with a domain object simplify usage and simplify the UI code



# APP RULES (LAYOUT)

All pages share a common application layout:

The image src/files/page-padding.png show how the UB is laid out
- A top toolbar which is 64px high.
- A sidebar on the left that is 200px wide.
- The remaining area is the usable body (UB) of the page.

The usable body (UB) layout:

The image src/files/page-padding.png shows how the UB is laid out
- Outer left and right padding: 48px.
- Outer top and bottom padding: 24px.
- Any direct child objects inside the UB (e.g. cards, sections) have **24px vertical spacing** between them.

Implementation rules:

- Do **not** reproduce this layout manually in each page.
- Create and use a shared layout component and/or SCSS utilities:

Example:

- Create `src/components/layout/PageLayout.jsx` and `PageLayout.module.scss`.
- `PageLayout` is responsible for:
  - Rendering the toolbar and sidebar.
  - Applying UB padding (48px/24px) and vertical spacing (24px between children).
- All pages should use `PageLayout`:

```jsx
// Example usage in a page
import PageLayout from '../../components/layout/PageLayout';

function UserPage() {
  return (
    <PageLayout title='Users'>
      {/* Direct children of PageLayout body get 24px spacing */}
      <UserSummaryCard />
      <UserTable />
    </PageLayout>
  );
}

export default UserPage;
